<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Indian government in a dilemma
over cotton sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KUNAL BOSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CALCUTTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DIFFERENCES between farmers and traders and textile mill operators over the
size of this year's Indian cotton crop are making it difficult for the
federal government to keep to its policy of authorising the export of at
least 500,000 bales a year.
The differences as to when the government should take a decision on the
export of new season staple cotton surfaced at last week's meeting of the
Cotton Advisory Board. The farmers, who are expecting a bumper crop of 13m
bales, pressed for immediate release of export quotas to avoid domestic
prices collapsing under the pressure of market arrivals.
The agriculture ministry supports this point of view but the Indian Cotton
Mills Federation, whose initial estimate of the current season's crop is 12m
bales, believes that in the interest of the textile industry, the government
should not make a decision until December, when the exact size of the crop
will be known. The textile ministry agrees.
According to industry officials, the standing crop is likely to be affected
to some extent by the present spell of heavy rain and by pest attacks in
some places.
In the meantime, the government has released an export quota of 126,000
bales of old season cotton for the Maharashtra State Co-operative Cotton
Marketing Federation and Cotton Corporation of India. The decision is being
taken as confirmation that the government is expecting an easy supply
situation in the present season.
Even if the crop is only 12m bales, the total availability for the season
will be 15.3m bales, including the carryover stock of 3.3m bales. The
industry's requirement is estimated at 1.05m bales while another 800,000 or
so bales are generally needed by the non-mill sector.
</TEXT>
