<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOLD fell again on the London bullion market yesterday, adding to Monday's
losses. The recent failure to break conclusively through resistance above
Dollars 350 a troy ounce has effectively capped the upside for the moment,
analysts say. If US funds now abandon positions established in the wake of
Europe's currency crisis - in spite of the likely volatility in financial
markets as the US elections approach - then gold could fall back to Dollars
340 and possibly August's lows at Dollars 335. The market could find some
support if the Bundesbank moves to cut interest rates tomorrow as rumoured
in the currency and equity markets. London COCOA prices reversed direction
in the afternoon, closing down. Dealers said there had been talk of light
selling of Ivorian cocoa with a modest strengthening in the value of the
pound versus the French franc making prices more attractive. COFFEE futures
finished easier, but above the day's lows, aided by the reversal of an early
fall in New York.
Compiled from Reuters
</TEXT>
