FT  14 OCT 92 / International Company News: Worldwide demand gives Motorola
38.7% advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MOTOROLA, the US elec-tronics manufacturer, reported a 38.7 per cent jump in
third-quarter earnings, boosted by strong demand across several product
segments in international markets.
Net earnings for the period rose to Dollars 129m, or 97 cents a share, from
Dollars 93m, or 70 cents, in the same quarter last year. Revenues rose 24
per cent to Dollars 3.4bn from Dollars 2.75bn.
Motorola said sales of its semiconductor products advanced 24 per cent to
Dollars 1.5bn in the quarter. Orders increased in the Asia-Pacific region,
Europe and the Americas, but were flat in Japan.
In the communications segment, sales were up 20 per cent to Dollars 1.04bn,
while computer systems sales jumped 42 per cent to Dollars 932m. The company
said demand for its digital wireless communications products rose in Asia
and the Pacific regions as well as Europe.
'The order growth in most of our businesses makes us optimistic about the
future,' said Mr George Fisher, chairman. 'About half of our sales are in
international markets, and we are seeing especially robust results in the
Asia-Pacific region outside of Japan.'
'While worldwide macroeconomic signals remain mixed, the outlook for growth
in the product markets we serve is brighter.'
The company said domestic orders rose in all major markets except the
government, where electronics group's sales declined 5 per cent.
For the first nine months, earnings increased to Dollars 402m, or Dollars
3.02 a share, from Dollars 328m, or Dollars 2.48 cents in the corresponding
period last year. Sales were Dollars 9.59bn, against Dollars 8.3bn.
</TEXT>
