<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / Producer prices rise by 3.2%: Slowest increase in factory
gate prices for 24 years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT received encouraging news on inflation yesterday as official
figures showed that prices of goods leaving Britain's factories rose at
their slowest rate for more than 24 years.
A report from the Central Statistical Office showed that prices for UK
manufactured goods in September were unchanged on the previous month. They
rose by 3.2 per cent in the year to September compared with 3.4 per cent in
the 12 months to August.
Excluding the volatile prices of food, drink and tobacco, the output price
index rose by 0.1 per cent last month, bringing the annual rate of increase
to 2.6 per cent, compared with 2.7 per cent in the year to August.
The prices of imported raw materials and fuels rose by a seasonally adjusted
0.2 per cent in September, compared with the previous month. The figures
provided the first indications of the effect of the sterling devaluation on
September 16.
In markets yesterday, combined with a stronger performance by the pound, the
better-than-expected news on producer price inflation fuelled hopes of a
further cut in banks' base rates from 9 per cent.
An announcement by Abbey National that it was to cut mortgage rates a
further 0.35 percentage points to 9.6 per cent gave a fillip to the FT-SE
100 share index which closed up 27.5 at 2,584.7. The pound, also buoyed by
earlier comments from Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, that he intended to
pay close attention to the exchange rate, closed up a pfennig in London at
DM2.52. In late New York trading, it was quoted at DM2.514.
But after gloomy news of coal pit closures, job losses and more business
failures, the government suffered further attacks yesterday for its handling
of the economy. Lord Prior, a former Conservative cabinet minster, accused
the Treasury of failing industry and warned of 'serious social problems' as
unemployment continued to rise.
The government was also criticised by Mr Howard Davies, director-general of
the CBI, who said businesses were increasingly frustrated at the lack of a
thought-out industrial strategy: 'We support the government's anti-inflation
stance and we support the government's aspirations to be at the heart of
Europe. But what we have been asking for time and time again is some
recognition that the government needs to set priorities for growth which
will address the underlying weaknesses of the economy.'
The 0.2 per cent monthly rise in the prices of raw materials and fuel
followed a 0.7 per cent fall in August. The full impact of more expensive
imported commodities, however, has yet to feed through. It is likely to be
felt over the coming months but the increases will not be passed on
automatically to finished goods. With consumer demand still very weak,
manufacturers are expected to absorb the higher costs generated by the
pound's devaluation.
'The input index will pop up quite sharply over the next few months, but it
will take a while before manufacturers pass that through,' said Mr Kevin
Gardiner, economist at SG Warburg Securities.
On an annual basis, input prices continued to fall albeit at a slower rate.
In the year to September the prices of raw materials fell by 0.4 per cent.
This compares with a fall of 1.5 per cent in the year to July and a fall of
1.1 per cent in the year to August.
Confidence falls, Page 13
</TEXT>
