<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / The Lex Column: A daring Touche
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Fund managers at Henderson and Touche Remnant would surely raise a quizzical
eyebrow if one of the industrial companies in their portfolios suddenly
announced that it was spending the bulk of a Pounds 55m cash hillock in its
balance sheet. It is, after all, no embarrassment in the City these days to
keep a little corporate money in the bank. By marking Henderson's shares 6
per cent higher, though, the stock market obviously believes that there are
valuable synergies to be had from merging two of the UK's biggest investment
management groups.
It is hard to make a firm judgment without the final price. The two product
ranges certainly appear complementary - thus boosting overall earnings
quality. Touche should bring a touch of class to the combined investment
performance. Henderson may be on the way back, but it has been through a
desperately rocky patch. The vital question is the scale of available cost
cutting which, failing a sustained bull market in equities, holds the
commercial key to the transaction. On the back-of-an-envelope assumption
that the Touche price tag might prove to be anything up to Pounds 45m - for
which the bidder would be getting Pounds 18m of cash as well as the funds
under management - Henderson shareholders will hope that Pounds 10m of
savings does not turn out to be an over-ambitious target.
It is fitting, of course, that the deal should have been announced within
days of the fifth anniversary of Black Monday - an event which wiped out
nearly 70 per cent of Henderson's market value overnight and marked such a
sudden change in the group's fortunes. The departure of Societe Generale is
also highly symbolic. It may be that unit trusts will one day be sold in
Lyon and Marseilles, and French Sicavs in Esher and Chipping Norton. But not
yet.
</TEXT>
