<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The 'public access' programme on BBC2, now called Open Space, looks more
professsional today than when it first started. Back in the early idealistic
days the idea was to hand over technology and assistance to members of the
public so they could really make their own programmes. The trouble is that
if you genuinely allow people full control you risk getting unwatchable
material. Today it is often difficult to see the difference between these
programmes and those in other current affairs slots.
Another series begins tonight with the story of Mordechai Vanunu, who was
kidnapped by Mossad and tried in Israel after his claims about Israel's
nuclear weapons programme (7.40).
Anyone who watched the opening episode of BBC2's bizarre drama serial
Downtown Lagos will surely want to see Part 2 (9.25): is it a legal yarn? A
story of wild colonial days? A drugs thriller? Who knows, yet it has style
and a powerful grip.
Channel 4 has two big attractions: the first episode in the final series of
the consistently funny Golden Girls (10.00) and another episode from the
crazy drama serial The Prisoner (11.15).
</TEXT>
