<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / Treasury management set-up to alter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TREASURY has altered its internal management structure to improve
decision-making after acting on suggestions from Mr Howard Davies, the
director-general of the Confederation of British Industry.
The move to set up an all-encompassing management board at the Treasury, in
place of a number of committees that decided on internal policies, is part
of a broad effort by the department to take on new ideas after criticism
that it has become cut off from academic economists and industry.
Sir Terry Burns, Treasury permanent secretary, asked Mr Davies for advice
last year. At that time, Mr Davies, who took over as head of the CBI in July
and is a former management consultant, was controller of the Audit
Commission, a government public-spending watchdog.
Mr Davies made his suggestions at a special meeting in the spring this year
with about 15 senior Treasury officials held at the chancellor's official
country residence.
The Treasury's new management board, headed by Sir Terry, includes the top
10 or so Treasury officials and meets once a week. It is largely concerned
with non-political judgments and does not in-clude government ministers.
The board replaces the Treasury's former policy co-ordinating committee
which considered broad questions of economic policy, and several other
loosely formed groups that considered questions of internal management such
as staff organisation.
Senior officials felt, after taking soundings from Mr Davies, that the
structure of the co-ordinating committee and the other committees had become
too unwieldy, which made it more difficult for the Treasury to focus its
thoughts and make timely decisions.
Mr Davies's work for the Treasury has now ended. He helped the Treasury,
unpaid, in his spare time from the Audit Commission. Some of the ideas
generated from his suggestions - such as the need for less secrecy, with
more contacts with outsiders - were outlined by Sir Terry to the Treasury's
top 70 officials at a meeting at the Institution of Civil Engineers earlier
this month.
Behind Sir Terry's decision to enlist Mr Davies for advice was the latter's
reputation as someone who combines knowledge of Whitehall with wide
experience in the business world. Mr Davies was a Treasury official for six
years until 1982, then spent the next five years with the McKinsey
management consultancy.
</TEXT>
