<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / Confidence 'falls through floor' in north
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS confidence has plunged in the Yorkshire area and Humberside,
according to preliminary figures collated by Leeds Chamber of Commerce.
They show rapid deterioration in home markets and reversal of rising trends
in exports.
The data were collected before September 16, when sterling left the exchange
rate mechanism. Mr Ian Kelly, assistant director of the chamber, said
yesterday: 'We can assume from anecdotal evidence that the state of trade is
now much worse. We have been bouncing along the bottom for months. We have
now fallen through the floor.'
The indicators, drawn from regular quarterly surveys of business carried out
by all chambers in the region, come a day after 10 chambers of commerce in
north-west England warned that serious losses of industrial capacity were
likely if demand continued to fall. The regions jointly account for up to 18
per cent of UK gross domestic product and contain the bulk of northern
England's manufacturing industry.
Leeds chamber yesterday released the trend indicators from the combined
results of the surveys in the form of balance figures - the difference
between companies reporting increases in any factor and those reporting
falls.
Among manufacturers, the balance figure fell by 20 percentage points for
home orders, 16 points for home deliveries, 22 points for export deliveries
and 18 points for export orders from the previous quarter. All the figures
are now negative - more companies reporting falls than increases - ranging
from - 3 percentage points for export deliveries to - 17 points for home
orders.
In June, all four figures were positive and recovering strongly. Combined
with the results from chambers in north-west England, the statistics point
to a marked double dip to recession throughout the M62 motorway corridor -
the main wealth-producing band of northern England.
The Yorkshire and Humberside survey covered 529 manufacturers employing
70,616 people and 886 service companies with 91,554 employees.
Service companies reported similar, but less severe, trends to
manufacturers. Home sales fell 17 points to a balance of - 10 points, while
home orders also fell 17 points, this time to - 12 points.
The balance of export sales by service companies remained positive at 6
points, down from 16 points in June and 13 in March. Export orders fared
worse - down to 3 percentage points from 17 points in June and 11 points in
the first quarter.
In all sectors, labour-shedding intensified, with yet more job losses
forecast for the present quarter, particularly in manufacturing.
</TEXT>
