<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / Cabinet may trim capital spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAPITAL PROJECTS are still among the areas that are likely to be cut as the
cabinet committee on public spending met yesterday and finished the second
stage of the public-expenditure round.
The six-strong committee, known in Whitehall as EDX, chaired by Mr Norman
Lamont, the chancellor, concluded its assessment of priorities for spending
in 1993-94. It will use its discussions today and tomorrow to focus on the
impact of those decisions on departmental programmes.
Officials are working towards an Autumn Statement in the week beginning
November 9, and the tough schedule of meetings is partly to compensate for
the decision not to continue the spending discussions during last week's
Tory party conference.
Ministers highlighted last week the need to keep the pressure on
public-sector pay and hinted at a squeeze on social security benefits.
Although they played down the more politically contentious course of cutting
back on capital spending, construction projects are still under threat.
Industrialists have already reacted with dismay to the prospect of large
reductions in capital investment, which is seen as having a vital
contribution to make to the survival of the construction industry.
Lord Prior, a former Tory cabinet minister and now chairman of GEC, the
defence group, said yesterday that it would be 'devastatingly bad' for
industry if the government cut back on capital projects in the present
public-spending review.
There are still ominous signs over some building expenditure. One Treasury
official highlighted the link between the signal in Mr John Major's speech
to conference last Friday about relaxing the rules for public and private
co-operation on infrastructure projects, and the expected cuts in the
Department of Transport's roads programme.
A few pieces of capital spending - such as central government support for
local light rail projects - have already been scrapped. Defence spending and
the Department of the Environment's housing budget have also been widely
identified as likely victims.
In spite of earlier suggestions that the Treasury might be trying to get
spending below the Pounds 244.5bn planning total for next year, the latest
signals are that the intention is to meet that target rather than cut
spending below it.
The Treasury keeps formally to the line that 'nothing is decided until
everything is decided'.
The view from spending departments, however, is that the first round of
'easy' cuts has already been made, and that the Treasury's aim now is to
give itself room to increase spending on a few high-priority programmes
while keeping within the overall target.
EDX has not yet decided whether departmental ministers should be invited to
put their arguments in person or whether they should have no opportunity to
query the committee's judgments until they go to full cabinet in early
November.
</TEXT>
