<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / Procter &amp; Gamble cancels claim in cosmetic advert
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROCTER &amp; GAMBLE, the US consumer product group, has retracted an
advertising claim that could have been understood to suggest that one of its
products - Clearasil, a medicated moisturiser - would leave every user
spot-free.
The magazine advertisement claimed: 'Moisturisers left me with spots; New
Clearasil moisturiser leaves me spot-free', and was subject to a complaint
that was upheld by the Advertising Standards Authority in its latest monthly
digest of complaints.
The ASA report said P&amp;G 're-examined their documentary evidence before
receiving the complaint' and 'recognised that it was insufficient to support
the impression that the product would necessarily leave every user spot-free
and they had discontinued the advertisement'.
The ASA upheld complaints against a number of other advertisements in the
health and dietary sectors, including promotions for products tackling
baldness, obesity and arthritis.
Complaints against Canon UK and Minolta, both on performance claims for
cameras, were upheld, as was a complaint against the London-based Institute
for Independent British Business.
The institute had taken out press advertising aimed at redundant and
early-retiring executives, claiming that annual income of Pounds 36,000
could be obtained, on a 12-month contract.
The advertisement failed to specify that the contract was available only to
those who participated in a development programme costing Pounds 6,227.50
and that, once employed, 20 per cent of the advertised annual earnings would
be payable to the advertisers.
</TEXT>
