<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / Health food group fined Pounds 1,000 over 'IQ' pills
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LARKHALL Natural Health, a health food company, was fined Pounds 1,000 and
ordered to pay Pounds 35,000 prosecution costs yesterday over claims that
its vitamin pills could improve the intelligence of children.
In a case brought by Shropshire trading standards officers, it was found
guilty of three charges of making false claims on packaging and literature
about Tandem IQ.
Mr Harry Hatchard, Shrewsbury stipendiary magistrate, said he did not regard
the marketing of the product as a deliberate hoax. He believed Dr Robert
Woodward, Larkhall chairman, genuinely thought the pills could enhance the
intelligence of children.
The company's offence was in not taking sufficient care in limiting claims.
The prosecution had alleged that labelling on the vitamin pill packets
conveyed the impression that the product could increase the IQ of the vast
majority of children.
There was no indication that only some children would benefit, said the
prosecution, which accepted that the claim could be true for a minority who
had a poor diet.
Mr Robin Spencer, for the trading standards department, said the letters
'IQ' on the front of the packaging were intended to convey 'intelligence
quotient'. He said the company had tried to disguise that inference by
stating on the back of the packets that IQ meant 'ideal quota'.
The magistrate said he was satisfied there was reliable evidence that only
children with a dietary deficiency were likely to benefit from vitamin and
mineral supplements.
He was also satisfied that a significant number of potential customers could
be misled into thinking that the tablets were capable of a general and
widespread effect in increasing the IQ of children.
</TEXT>
