<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / Kosovo protest is crushed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SERBIAN police yesterday used tear gas and truncheons to disperse a
demonstration by ethnic Albanians in Pristina, Kosovo, the mostly Albanian
province in southern Serbia.
Army jets swooped over the Kosovo capital as the protesters gathered for the
second day, demanding the opening of Albanian language schools and
university.
Mr Ibrahim Rugova, the Albanian leader, said in Pristina yesterday the
violent break-up of the demonstration was a provocation by Serbian President
Slobodan Milosevic intended to show he still controlled the province.
Scores were killed in 1989 when the Serbian president forcibly brought
Kosovo under direct rule by Belgrade. Mr Milosevic may use Kosovo, seen by
Serbs as the cradle of their civilisation, to rally popular support in
Serbia, flagging after 15 months of war and United Nations sanctions.
Mr Milan Panic, the Yugoslav prime minister, said yesterday it would be
easier to get sanctions lifted if Mr Milosevic resigned. Mr Milosevic is
seen by the international community as the main instigator of the war in
Bosnia.
To re-integrate Kosovo's 1.9m ethnic Albanian population into Yugoslavia, Mr
Panic has pledged to reform the educational system, boycotted by Albanians
after Serbia imposed its own curriculum.
The United States was last night consulting its allies on ways to enforce a
no-fly zone over Bosnia-Hercegovina and considering pushing for a tougher
United Nations resolution, Reuter reports from Washington. The UN Security
Council imposed the no-fly zone last Friday.
State Department spokesman Joe Snyder said Bosnian Serbs flew numerous
sorties, including bombing raids, on Saturday. There were no flights on
Sunday and Monday but Bosnian Serb aircraft started operating again
yesterday, he said. However, UN officials said there had been no violations
since Saturday.
Meanwhile Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, has offered to
remove all his aircraft from Bosnia and station them at airfields in the
rump Yugoslav state under UN observers. The UN said Mr Karadzic made the
offer at Geneva yesterday in a meeting with Lord Owen, co-chairman of the
peace conference, in an attempt to facilitate implementation of the
resolution on the no-fly zone.
</TEXT>
