<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / AWD bought by defence company
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AWD, THE former Bedford trucks business that went into receivership in June,
has been sold for an undisclosed sum to a subsidiary of Marshall of
Cambridge, the privately owned UK aerospace and defence support services
contractor.
The purchase will almost certainly mark the end of truck making at AWD's
Dunstable plant after more than 50 years - but it also means that the long
Bedford tradition as a manufacturer of both military and civilian trucks is
likely to be preserved and strengthened.
AWD's product designs and most of its assets are being transferred to
Marshall SPV (special production vehicles).
Originally established as Marshall of Cambridge (Engineering) to make
vehicle bodies and exploit the international market for specialist military
vehicles such as field ambulances, it changed its name to Marshall SPV
earlier this year. It has been seeking to extend its activities in the
civilian vehicles field and its product range now includes refuse disposal
vehicles, single-decker buses, and car transporters and trailers. Recently,
it also acquired Carlisle, the Birmingham-based bus maker.
Marshall, a reticent company that prefers to conduct its affairs out of the
public spotlight, employs 2,500 people - mostly at its sprawling
airfield-based headquarters near Cambridge.
Under its purchase agreement with Mr Tony Thompson and Mr Roger Oldfield of
KPMG Peat Marwick, the joint receivers, Marshall is buying AWD's product
designs, global spare parts business, order book and the rights to the AWD
and Bedford names.
It is taking a short lease on the 45-acre Dunstable plant, where the
receivers have been employing 150 former AWD workers to build about five
trucks a week.
AWD had stopped making trucks for several months before the receivers moved
in. 'However, we wanted to sell AWD as a going concern, got some orders
ourselves - mostly from the military and overseas - and were able to restart
production,' Mr Thompson said yesterday. Marshall is to employ some of the
Dunstable workers on a temporary basis, but is expected to move production
to its Cambridge site in the longer term.
Commenting on the takeover, Mr Bernard Williams, managing director of SPV,
said: 'In AWD we have acquired products with a tremendous reputation in the
specialist market for four-wheel-drive trucks. We believe that there is
synergy between the AWD products and Marshall SPV which will prove of great
benefit to us with our plans for further expansion in civil and military
markets worldwide.'
AWD, then named Bedford Trucks, was bought from General Motors in 1987 for
about Pounds 20m by Mr David Brown, a Yorkshire entrepreneur.
Under GM's ownership, Bedford had been losing Pounds  1/2 m a week in a
plant that had the capacity to produce 60,000 trucks a year and which, up to
the start of the 1980s, had employed 6,000 people.
At its peak under Mr Brown's ownership AWD was employing more than 1,300,
and he spoke of creating a company employing more than 2,000 people and
building 10,000 trucks annually.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
