FT  13 OCT 92 / SA government and Inkatha to meet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAPE TOWN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR FW de Klerk, the South African president, said yesterday that government
officials would meet the mainly Zulu Inkatha Freedom party within a
fortnight, removing one of the most serious obstacles to the resumption of
multi-party talks on a new constitution.
Delivering a 'state of the nation' address to a special session of
parliament in Cape Town, he stressed his determination to proceed with
constitutional negotiations with the ANC and other parties, including
Inkatha which suspended talks with the government two weeks ago.
He lashed out, however, at the African National Congress shortly after
thousands of ANC protesters surrounded the parliament building. He demanded
that the organisation scale down its campaign of mass action which he blames
for exacerbating political violence in South Africa.
The ANC demonstration, called to protest at the continued exclusion of
blacks from parliament and at government plans to amnesty police and army
officers, was much smaller than expected. Only about 5,000 people took part.
Organisers had expected a crowd of 25,000.
Top ANC leaders addressed the crowd, which formed a human chain around the
parliament building. 'We want this place closed down and replaced by a
people's parliament,' South African Communist party veteran Joe Slovo
demanded. 'The people have no vote here. The only parliament you can
participate in is the parliament of the streets,' he said.
ANC leaders condemned government plans to introduce legislation in
parliament within the next 10 days to amnesty security force officers who
committed crimes under apartheid.
Mr de Klerk outlined principles on which he demanded agreement before an
interim constitution could be agreed, including devolution of power to
regional and local governments, multi-party power sharing at the executive
level of government, and a bicameral legislature to protect special
interests. The ANC and government positions on all of these issues remain
sharply at odds.
