<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 92 / International Company News: Bidder for Continental Airlines
drops out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF the potential bidders for Continental Airlines, the US carrier which
has been operating under Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection since late 1990,
withdrew from the running yesterday.
Benefit Concepts, a New York-based firm which was designing an offer which
utilised employee stock ownership plan (ESOP) debt in conjunction with
former executives of the airline, said it was abandoning the effort because
of Continental's refusal to supply confidential financial information.
Continental, by contrast, said Benefit Concepts failed to meet the standards
of a 'qualifying bidder', and hence was not entitled to the information.
So far, three outline investment proposals - from Mr Hurwitz's Maxxam group,
from Mr Alfredo Brener's Houston Air, and from Air Canada in conjunction
with a Texan investment partnership - have met the qualification
requirements.
The approach from Lufthansa, in conjunction with Mr Marvin Davis, the
Californian investor, is still be evaluated. A deadline of November 9 was
recently set for all bidders to submit proposals.
</TEXT>
