<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 92 / Economies no better under PR
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
DIFFERENCES between the economic performance of countries cannot be
explained by differences in their electoral systems, according to a study
published yesterday by the Electoral Reform Society.
Proportional representation is neither the threat to economic progress
alleged by the prime minister, nor a panacea for the UK's economic ills as
claimed by the Liberal Democrats and other supporters, the society says.
The study, by Professor Richard Rose of Strathclyde University, compares
five economic indicators for 21 OECD countries to see whether there is any
link between their economic performance and their electoral system.
It finds virtually no difference between countries with proportional
representation and those with first-past-the-post systems in their average
annual growth rates, debt interest as a proportion of GDP or unemployment
rates.
Public expenditure and inflation have risen faster on average in countries
with proportional representation.
What are the Economic Consequences of Proportional Representation? Electoral
Reform Society, 6 Chancel Street, London SE1 0UU. Pounds 15.
</TEXT>
