<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 92 / UK Company News: Tay dips 26% but lifts payment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WALTON MORAIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TAY HOMES, the Leeds-based housebuilder, saw year-end pre-tax profits dip 26
per cent in depressed conditions. But turnover increased as it sold more
than 1,000 houses for the first time and it cut gearing.
An increased final dividend of 4.65p was declared, making 5.85p (5.3p) for
the year.
Taxable profits in the year to June 30 1992 declined to Pounds 6.14m (Pounds
8.26m) on sales of Pounds 76.22m (Pounds 70.58m). Operating profits were
down to Pounds 9.25m (Pounds 11.63m).
Reduced gearing of 47 per cent (66 per cent) on borrowings of Pounds 14.2m
was partly due to a shift of costs on a show house joint venture being
shifted off the balance sheet. Interest charges fell to Pounds 3.11m (Pounds
3.37m).
Mr Trevor Spencer, chairman, said the year-end figures were an excellent
achievement in uniquely difficult conditions. He said that while a forecast
was difficult, the group's ability to generate profit reflected its capacity
to weather the recession and recover strongly when conditions improved.
Sales of houses, mainly in Yorkshire, rose to 1,094 from 849. The Midlands
was also strong but trading in Scotland declined. Average prices dipped to
Pounds 64,900 (Pounds 74,300), reflecting a focus on cheaper housing.
Sales of mainly Scottish plots from the group's land bank, which stood at
4,800 units at year-end, totalled Pounds 1.4m (Pounds 2.3m).
Funds tied up in part-exchange homes totalled Pounds 5.8m (Pounds 5.2m) at
year-end.
Shareholders funds rose to Pounds 30.31m (Pounds 28.05m) representing assets
per share of 138.2p (127.9p). Earnings declined to 18.1p (25.1p).
</TEXT>
