<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 92 / Lucas to lose 4,000 jobs in shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LUCAS Industries, one of the UK's largest engineering groups, is shedding at
least 4,000 jobs in a three-year restructuring programme. It will sell
companies which are not central to its aerospace and automotive business and
move its manufacturing operations on to fewer sites.
To pay for the restructuring, the group made a provision of Pounds 88.4m in
its 1991-92 results. The figures, announced yesterday, showed a sharp
reduction in pre-tax profits to Pounds 22.5m from Pounds 82.8m in the year
to July 1991, and a net loss of Pounds 8.8m compared with a net profit of
Pounds 49.4m last time. Lucas had a loss per share of 1.2p, against earnings
per share of 7.1p a year earlier.
The performance came as no surprise to the stock market which was heartened
by the maintenance of the dividend at 7p a share. The share price quickly
climbed 10p before settling to close at 94p for a day's rise of 4p. This
gave Lucas a market value of nearly Pounds 660m.
Lucas started its restructuring programme earlier this year. It has already
reduced its workforce by 1,250. The remaining 2,750 jobs will be lost,
roughly evenly, between the UK and overseas, taking the total number of
people employed worldwide by the group to around 47,000 from more than
57,000 in July, 1990.
Sir Anthony Gill, chairman, warned that the first half of the current year
will be little better than the 1991-92 first half, when Lucas had pre-tax
profits of Pounds 200,000 topped up by a Pounds 90m contribution from its
pension fund.
The pension fund contribution is offsetting the future cost of the
restructuring programme. In 1991-92 Lucas had in any case paid Pounds 23.7m
in redundancy and reorganisation costs. These sliced into trading profits
and left operating profits at Pounds 58.3m, half the previous year, but
earned on sales 5 per cent down at Pounds 2.37bn.
Lucas found all its aerospace markets weaker: operating profits were reduced
in the UK while losses were incurred in North America and continental
Europe.
By comparison, its automotive business had a glittering year. Operating
profits at Pounds 38.6m nearly reached the level of the previous year and
sharply higher profits in continental Europe more than offset losses in the
UK and North America.
Lex, Page 22
New components, Page 24
