<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 92 / DTI to query photocopier sales tactics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEPARTMENT of Trade and Industry is to raise with the Office of Fair
Trading renewed allegations of unscrupulous sales tactics by photocopier
salesmen.
The move follows a meeting last week between Baroness Denton, the DTI
minister responsible for consumer affairs, and members of the Campaign to
Clean Up Copier Contracts, which has the support of the Confederation of
British Industry.
More than 1,500 companies have complained to the campaign about very high
hidden costs in 'copy plan' contracts, which amalgamate the capital and
running costs of photocopiers into a single charge and charge customers on a
'per copy' basis.
There have been allegations that some finance companies add the concealed
cost of settling earlier photocopier agreements to the cost of new capital
equipment.
Many companies complain that they are unwittingly signing leasing deals
lasting up to nine years for equipment with a three-year life. Any variation
in copier requirements can mean that the contract period starts again.
The campaign leaders told Baroness Denton that, in spite of an OFT
investigation into the activities of one photocopier distributor in 1991 and
attempts by some trade organisations to enforce new codes of conduct in the
leasing market, evidence remains of widespread malpractice involving
photocopy contracts.
The OFT says it will consider revoking consumer credit licences if
leasing-contract abuses are discovered.
Lady Denton has been given a portfolio of cases alleging misrepresentation
and possible fraud.
She is being pressed to pursue changes in the law to offer companies a
two-week 'cooling off' period once contracts are signed.
The campaign also wants businesses to have the same protection available to
individuals under the Consumer Credit Act.
The campaign has announced the establishment of a panel of lawyers and
accountants who will analyse complaints, identify the biggest offenders and
provide advice on how contracts can be challenged.
The DTI confirmed that the issue would be discussed at its next scheduled
meeting with the OFT.
</TEXT>
