<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 92 / Carlton TV ready to take on franchise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CARLTON Television, winner of the London weekday franchise, put on a glitzy
face yesterday for its first presentation to advertisers at the London
Palladium.
Carlton will take over from Thames Television at midnight on January 1 and
is putting Pounds 92m into the ITV national network schedule plus Pounds 11m
into regional programmes apart from a Pounds 7m contribution to setting up a
seven-days-a-week news operation with London Weekend Television.
Mr Nigel Warmsley, chief executive of Carlton Television, promised to offer
'both continuity and change'. The changes include a daily one-hour magazine
programme about life in the capital. There is continuity in the reappearance
of entertainers such as Dave Allen and the transformation of Nicholas
Parsons and his radio programme Just A Minute into a television programme.
Current affairs will include a documentary on Vietnam 20 years after the
Paris Treaty and there will be education in the form of the Good Sex Guide.
The typographical Carlton, the designers have decreed, will in future will
have a small 't' tucked into the capital 'L' and the company will be branded
on screen by 70 people, famous and not so famous, emphasising the theme
'Television For London'.
Ms Christine Walker, chief executive of Zenith Media, the UK's largest media
buyer, and one of those appearing in the Television For London promotions,
was relieved at what she saw yesterday. She said: 'I was afraid they would
go for designer television. They haven't. It's safe but I don't think
they'll match the ratings of Thames this year.'
Not surprisingly, the franchise losers have been maximising their audience
figures and their advertising earnings in their final year as broadcasters.
</TEXT>
