FT  13 OCT 92 / Canary Wharf banks seek more time over Tube cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ADMINISTRATORS of Canary Wharf, the financially troubled east London
property development, asked the Government last night for time to revise
their offer of a contribution to the costs of building the Jubilee Line Tube
extension.
The administrators, three partners of the accountancy firm Ernst &amp; Young,
met Lord Wakeham, the leader of the Lords, who is chairing a government
committee on London Docklands. They were accompanied by Lord Griffiths, Lady
Thatcher's former adviser, who is now international adviser at Goldman
Sachs, the US investment bank working for the administrators.
The administrators and Canary Wharf's 11 commercial banks had faced a
deadline of the end of September for making an offer of private-sector funds
for the Tube project. Yesterday they sought a later deadline for two
reasons.
First, they had believed that the government was planning to move Department
of Environment officials to Canary Wharf. If the staff are to stay in
central London, as government officials have hinted, the banks need time to
assess the implications.
Second, the administrators had not understood that the government was
opposed in principle to an offer of private-sector funds being conditional
on government support.
Three weeks ago the banks offered Pounds 390m towards the Jubilee Line's
Pounds 1.6bn costs, but the fact that the offer was conditional on civil
servants moving to Canary Wharf made the offer unaccceptable to the
government.
