<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 92 / Incentives 'too small to boost training'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YOUNG PEOPLE often are reluctant to pursue vocational training because the
financial rewards are too small, according to a report published today by
the London School of Economics, Lisa Wood writes.
The report said pay differentials between unskilled workers and those with
low-level vocational qualifications were slim, although people with degrees
or high-level vocational qualifications could command more pay.
'If wages remain high for low and unskilled jobs, why should any one bother
to obtain further training?' the report said.
The authors said differentials were often insufficient to make training
worthwhile, so reluctance to pursue training was often perfectly rational.
The report, paid for by BP, implies that employers over time should hold
down pay rates of the unqualified and raise those of skilled workers. It
could also be interpreted as suggesting that low-level vocational
qualifications are not of a sufficiently high standard to warrant higher
pay.
Learning Should Pay. BP Educational Services, PO Box 934, Poole, Dorset
BH177BR. Free.
