<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 92 / Car remains most common perk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CAR is still the most common perk offered by British companies, although
one in five is now letting employees trade cars for a higher salary.
The findings, published yesterday by the Confederation of British Industry,
indicate that employee benefits have not generally been cut during the
recession, although companies are tightening up on administration costs.
The CBI said it was surprised that perks had survived relatively unscathed,
in view of the heavy costs they added to pay bills. Benefits typically add
10 per cent to 15 per cent to the salary costs of basic-level employees, and
40 per cent to 50 per cent for executives.
At very senior levels, benefits might add up to as much as, or more than,
the salary itself, the CBI said.
The survey was carried out with management consultants Towers Perrin and is
said to be the largest of its kind ever conducted in the UK. More than 600
organisations with a combined workforce of about 3m were questioned.
Almost all companies surveyed - 98 per cent - offer cars to at least some of
their employees. Cars even outstripped pensions, which were provided by 93
per cent of companies, and life assurance, also offered by 93 per cent.
Bottom of the perks league were vouchers for childcare, at 2 per cent, with
on-site creches not far ahead on 4 per cent.
The CBI said the survey highlighted the way benefits policies were lagging
behind changes in the workforce. Companies said the main change in their
workforces was the growth in the number of employees with spouses who were
also earning.
Almost as many cited an increase in employees' average ages and an increase
in the number of women workers.
Companies had not adapted benefits to those changes. In particular, little
account had been taken of the increase in dual-income families, and it was
possible that some benefits were being unnecessarily duplicated.
For example, a majority of companies continued to pay for private medical
insurance cover for spouses when it was possible that those spouses now
qualified for medical cover in their own right. There was also evidence that
older workers valued non-monetary benefits such as being allowed to increase
their supervisory role and act as mentors to younger colleagues, the CBI
said.
Many employers are reviewing their policies on cars because of increasing
costs and because forthcoming Inland Revenue reforms may mean that tax
payments increase by up to 40 per cent for company car drivers. Companies in
the financial sector and those with US parents were leading the field in
substituting cash for company cars or eliminating car schemes altogether,
the survey found.
While many employees were now taking money instead of cars, the same
flexibility was not on offer for other benefits. Pensions were offered on a
flexible basis by 7 per cent of the companies but more than 3 per cent of
employers offered choice on no other perk.
The Benefits Package of the Future, by CBI and Towers Perrin. CBI, 103 New
Oxford Street, London WC1. Pounds 10 to CBI members, Pounds 20 non-members.
</TEXT>
