<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 92 / Shake-up planned for Scots councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT spelt out options yesterday for a drastic reshaping of local
government in Scotland, sweeping away the two-tier structure established in
1974 and creating between 15 and 51 new single-tier councils.
The new system, which would come into effect in 1996, would entail changes
to Scotland's nine regional councils, including the disappearance of
Labour-dominated Strathclyde regional council, which contains nearly half
Scotland's 5m people.
A consultation document presenting options for the single-tier system quotes
the conclusion of Touche Ross, the accountants, that provided there were no
more than 43 councils the new system would lead to long-term savings of
public expenditure.
Initially, the savings would be exceeded by transitional expenses.
Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, said the existing system, brought in by the
Conservatives, was inconsistent with the present needs of local government.
It had been designed at a time when the public sector was expected to lead
economic development and deliver a wide range of services.
People wanted to be better able to identify who was responsible. People
found it hard to identify with the large regional authorities and still
often thought of themselves as living in the old counties or burghs.
There was also confusion for many people about which services were provided
by the regional councils and which by the 53 district councils, while there
was some overlap between them.
Launching a consultation process, backed by an explanatory video, Mr Lang
said he wanted a system that reflected local loyalties and was
cost-effective and efficient.
The new councils did not have to be of uniform size and he had 'an open
mind' on the most appropriate structure.
In England, a commission under Sir John Banham is touring the country,
deciding where new authorities should be. The Welsh Office has already
issued a document spelling out where single-tier authorities will be in
Wales.
One of the four options set out in yesterday's green paper for Scotland is
for 15 single-tier authorities. That would allow eight of the regional
councils to remain, absorbing the functions of the districts - Strathclyde
would be split.
The structure of local government in Scotland. Shaping the new councils.
Room 6/87, New St Andrew's House, Edinburgh EH1 3SZ. Free.
</TEXT>
