<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 92 / North-west confidence nosedives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A WARNING that north-west England faces a serious loss of manufacturing and
business capacity without a significant increase in economic activity was
issued yesterday by the area's chambers of commerce.
The chambers' regular quarterly survey for the July-September period shows a
huge slide in confidence as orders fell sharply. While 34 per cent of
manufacturers expected an improvement in profits in the next 12 months, 33
per cent forecast deterioration. The difference between the two of 1
percentage point is the trend indicator; it was 30 percentage points in
June.
Manchester chamber's economics committee called for a short-term stimulus,
which it said was unlikely to affect inflation much while demand was so low.
It said there would be further serious losses of industrial capacity without
significantly higher activity.
'The deteriorating position is reflected in reduced domestic orders,
continuing low capacity utilisation and poor cash flow,' the committee said.
The survey shows that nearly all improvements in trends in the last 12
months were wiped out. Manufacturing investment has been cut and more than
80 per cent of companies have spare capacity. The study covered 427
manufacturers employing 52,400 people, 289 service-sector companies with
30,600 employees, and 31 businesses not classified by sector employing 5,200
people.
Although service-sector businesses show a 12-point positive balance - 39 per
cent forecasting improvements versus 27 per cent predicting falls - that
contrasts with a 50-point balance for the second quarter.
The slide in business confidence is the result of a marked deterioration in
domestic orders. Only 26 per cent of manufacturers and 31 per cent of
service providers report more orders than in the second quarter, compared
with 44 per cent and 33 per cent respectively, which report falls.
Export sales faltered, with the second quarter's positive balance of 14
percentage points among manufacturers dropping to 3 points.
Employment markets worsened, after five successive quarters of slowdown in
job-shedding. There was a significant drop in the balance figure of
companies expecting to take on more labour - from 7 percentage points to 1
point.
Cash flow difficulties are described as 'serious'. Only 19 per cent of
businesses saw an improvement and 33 per cent saw a deterioration.
The 10 chambers in the survey cover Greater Manchester and Lancashire.
</TEXT>
