FT  13 OCT 92 / Brussels 'green' charges rejected
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday accused Brussels of acting with insensitivity as it
dismissed claims that the UK will be taken to the European Court of Justice
for three breaches of environmental laws on wild birds and emissions of
nitrous oxide.
Mr Michael Howard, environment secretary, was called to defend the
government's 'green' record at yesterday's relaunch of a campaign to
persuade householders to save energy and help to prevent global warming.
He said: 'We have received no communication whatsoever from the European
Commission on these issues since before the general election in April.' He
thought the disputes had been 'amicably resolved'.
Brussels has sent reasoned opinions to the government - the last step before
court action - for allowing farmers to shoot wild 'pest species' such as
crows, starlings and magpies, and for alleged failure to provide enough
'special protection areas' for wild birds.
A third dispute over the 'failure' to monitor levels of nitrous oxide is
less advanced. Mr Howard said he did not expect any of the arguments to end
in court.
