<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 92 / Lamont defends his actions on Black Wednesday: Peter Marsh
outlines the main points that emerged from the chancellor's appearance
yesterday before members of the Commons Treasury and Civil Service committee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVENTS leading up to Black Wednesday, September 16: Mr Lamont said he had
heard nothing since September 16 that pointed to any alternative to the
forced exit from the European exchange rate mechanism due to the intense
currency pressures. He said sterling's former central rate in the mechanism
of DM2.95 was not too onerous for Britain. To have raised interest rates
before Black Wednesday would have 'undermined, not strengthened' Britain's
position. 'Frankly, the game was up by Wednesday and we had no option but to
withdraw (as a result of the extreme strains on the pound),' he said.
ERM realignment: Mr Lamont wanted to make 'absolutely clear' that the
government had received no request from the German authorities in the
weekend before Black Wednesday for the pound to realign, along with the
lira. During the week in which the pound left the ERM, the possibility of a
unilateral devaluation of sterling, while staying within the ERM, had not
been under discussion. The chancellor said he had seen what happened to
Italy, which devalued only to see the lira under further intense pressure,
eventually requiring it to leave the system. Benefits from ERM membership:
The government had succeeded in bringing down inflation from nearly 11 per
cent to less than 4 per cent, measured by the year-on-year increase in the
retail prices index. The difference between UK and German interest rates had
narrowed substantially since October 1990, when the UK joined the ERM.
Future membership of the ERM: Britain would re-enter 'in due course' when
various conditions were met, including monetary conditions in the UK and
Germany being closer to alignment. It was 'quite impractical' to talk of a
return until those conditions were met. It would be possible for Britain to
ratify the Maastricht treaty without having agreed to re-enter the ERM.
Exchange rate: Outside the ERM, Mr Lamont attached 'a lot of importance to
the exchange rate', but ruled out any explicit target for the pound against
other main currencies. He would take the exchange rate into account when
framing monetary policy. 'The exchange rate is a very important part of
policy; we can't let the exchange rate go,' he said.
Inflation: The inflation target announced by Mr Lamont last week set
'demanding' challenges for Britain. Inflation had to be kept at between 1
per cent and 4 per cent, measured by the year-on-year rate in the retail
prices index, excluding mortgage interest payments. The Treasury would
attempt to monitor inflationary conditions by studying a range of monetary
indicators. Future inflation performance: Inflation must come down further.
'The current rate is still not nearly good enough for this country,' Mr
Lamont said, bearing in mind the better inflation performance of many of the
UK's competitors. 'I have brought down inflation (under ERM membership) and
I don't want to see it moved up again.'
Effects of intervention to support sterling: Mr Lamont acknowledged that the
large purchases of sterling by the Bank of England on Black Wednesday -
which some estimates put at up to Pounds 15bn - had a contractionary effect
on the economy by reducing the amount of money in the banking system. Some
aspects of that, however, were counter-acted by Bank money market
operations. He refused to put a figure on the intervention as the sum was
'market-sensitive'.
Monetary policy since Black Wednesday: Base rates had come down by 1
percentage point to 9 per cent, while there had been an effective
devaluation of roughly 10 per cent as measured by sterling's trade-weighted
index. The combination of those developments added up to a significant
loosening of monetary policy. Britain would not, however, have a 'growth
target'. The government's main economic efforts would be concentrated on
bringing down inflation.
Interest rates: Mr Lamont gave no firm comment about the direction of
interest rates, but in response to questioning from MPs about the continuing
recession said he would not 'kickstart the economy by giving it an
artificial stimulus'. Public spending: It would not be right to increase
public spending because 'such increases cannot be afforded'. However, the
Treasury would attempt to exclude capital spending projects as far as
possible from the effects of any cuts.
ERM fault lines: Those had arisen in recent months largely because of the
'unique' circumstances of German re-unification, which had pushed up German
credit rates, and the lack of symmetry between the economies of Germany and
the US. That had led to a strong D-Mark at the expense of the dollar,
straining a number of ERM currencies, among them sterling. It was 'not
inevitable', however, that fixed exchange-rate systems broke down. The ERM
had performed a useful function for more than a decade in helping currency
stability and adding to disinflationary pressures. However, there were
technical aspects of ERM membership that could be usefully addressed, such
as the rules related to when central banks should intervene to support
currencies.
Mr Lamont's future: Mr Lamont said it was 'complete nonsense' that he should
stand down as chancellor. He had presided over a 'remarkable' reduction in
inflation which was 'not an inconsiderable achievement'.
Forecasting: It was fallacious to say whether the Treasury model of how the
economy worked was good or bad; everything in forecasts depended on what
numbers and judgments were fed to the models. 'I repeat what I have always
said, which is that all forecasts should be treated with caution and
scepticism,' he said. As for the future, Mr Lamont said 'no one would like
to see an (economic) recovery more than me'. But there was a limit as to
what governments could do to promote one.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-14015</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJMCIABEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921013
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 92 / World Trade News: Trade partners close together yet so far
apart
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
'THERE have been more near-misses on this than Bosnian ceasefires,' a senior
US diplomat observed recently. He wondered how it was that while the EC and
US share an interest in concluding Gatt's Uruguay Round world trade talks
and are seemingly near in their positions, they are still separated by what
each sees as vital national interests.
On subsidies to farmers, an issue that has held up agreement since the
Uruguay Round summit collapsed in Brussels in December 1990, the US, EC and
other leading agri-exporters are trying to position themselves in export
markets, especially cereals.
France threatened to pull out of next Friday's EC summit in Birmingham if
the latest EC-US talks in Brussels gave away to the US too much of its food
exporting 'vocation'.
As the EC's agricultural superpower, France has concentrated its attack on a
Gatt provision to cut subsidised food exports 24 per cent on all products.
This would be a blow to its wheat trade, the most sensitive commodity for
the US alongside soya beans, on which it is conducting a parallel row with
the EC. The need to cut subsidised exports, contained in the Round's 'final
act' which Gatt drew up last December, is separate to, and on top of, a 36
per cent cut in money paid out on export subsidies.
At July's Group of Seven Munich summit, the UK proposed export volume be cut
by 21, not 24 per cent.
Mr Ray MacSharry, EC agriculture commissioner, has pushed for 'aggregation'
or flexibility in farm sectors. This way the EC could export more wheat, for
instance, if it sold less barley abroad, provided overall cuts in grain
exports reached the target.
The full 24 per cent cut, if it contains this flexibility, is a much better
deal for the EC than a far lower cut without it.
The US knows this, and that the reform of the EC's Common Agricultural
Policy (CAP), agreed in May, will cut European wheat prices to near world
market levels.
The real difference between the two sides on export volume is about
competition, and French wheat is very competitive.
If May's CAP reform had cut guaranteed prices a bit further, export
subsidies would have been scrapped well within the life of any Uruguay Round
agreement, and the US would have been hard pressed to seek restraints on EC
exporters. France would have been the main beneficiary from a slightly
bigger cut.
The second big difference to be resolved is for how long EC compensation
payments to farmers for the CAP reform price cuts will be exempt from
reductions prescribed by Gatt. Mr MacSharry wants indefinite exemption,
because the payments are compensation for price cuts and production cuts.
The US, if the cuts in output are formalised, is ready to exempt the
payments for only six years.
It is still possible Mr MacSharry might relent if the point is established
that if these payments do cut output and reduce trade tensions, they should
be exempt in the next round of cuts.
</TEXT>
