<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 92 / Lamont rules out 'kickstart': Cutting inflation stays at
heart of economic policy, chancellor tells MPs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Norman Lamont, the chancellor, yesterday underlined that UK economic
policy would continue to aim at cutting inflation and rejected any idea of
'kickstarting the economy' to produce faster growth.
In a dogged performance before the all-party Commons Treasury and Civil
Service committee, the chancellor said the government would pay very careful
attention to the sterling exchange rate in formulating monetary policy.
Stressing that the UK had no exchange rate target now that it had left the
European exchange rate mechanism, he nevertheless said he would 'attach
particular importance' to the pound's movements against the Bank of
England's trade weighted index of currencies.
He also said that Britain's inflation rate - currently 4 per cent on the
Treasury's measure of underlying inflation - would have to 'come down
further'. The UK had to compete with countries with lower inflation.
Mr Lamont's evidence, given in an occasionally barbed two-hour session, shed
no new light on how the government would use the various monetary and
financial indicators it has chosen as guides to monetary policy when setting
interest rates.
He did not say when sterling might return to the ERM, insisting only that it
would be 'quite impractical' to rejoin the mechanism before economic and
monetary conditions in the UK and Germany were more compatible.
In what could be a move to give the government leeway before re-entering the
ERM, he repeatedly said that the UK would be able to ratify the Maastricht
treaty on closer European union without first having sterling back in the
mechanism.
The emphasis the chancellor placed on curbing inflation and the need to
avoid a free fall in sterling persuaded some City commentators that he would
be in no rush to cut interest rates further.
Opinion on the domestic money market has been moving in the direction of a
cut in rates in recent days. Three months money, a key indicator of how the
market thinks base rates are moving, closed at around 8 per cent yesterday
compared with bank base rates at 9 per cent.
Mr Bill Martin, chief UK economist of UBS Phillips and Drew, the City
securities house, said he thought the government would now 'keep markets
waiting' for interest rate cuts, but would act after periods of stability or
strength for sterling.
By avoiding any serious mistakes in his testimony, Mr Lamont appeared to
have reassured Tory MPs yesterday that he could give a robust justification
for his economic policies. But although he emerged from the
cross-examination by MPs with his standing at Westminster at least no worse
than before, speculation continued over how long he could remain at the
Treasury.
Conservative MPs appeared content with his apparent no-score draw. 'I don't
think that there was anything today that undermined his position and I would
have thought that he would probably have strengthened it,' Mr John Watts,
the committee's Tory chairman, said.
But Mr Lamont is vulnerable to attacks from Labour that there is a vacuum in
his economic policy. Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, said on Channel 4
News the chancellor's performance was 'appalling'. The chancellor had said
'not a word about growth, about bringing down unemployment and strengthening
industry'.
However, Mr Lamont told the committee that he did not believe in
'kickstarting the economy by artificial stimulus'.
He rejected higher public spending and although he said that the government
would do its best to safeguard capital spending, 'at the end of the day' it
was the overall control of public spending that mattered.
Questioned about the circumstances of Britain's departure from the ERM, Mr
Lamont denied the substance of reports that the UK's EC partners had
suggested a broader realignment of the ERM, including a devaluation of
sterling, during September 12-13 when the Italian lira was devalued.
However, the controversy looks set to continue after Mr Horst Kohler, the
state secretary in the Bonn finance ministry, said that Britain refused an
offer to realign sterling in the ERM before Black Wednesday.
Talking on BBC TV's Panorama last night, he said: 'Together with the
Bundesbank we came to the conclusion it would be the right decision to make
a broad realignment in the EMS, including the lira, the British pound, and
maybe other currencies, in order to ease tensions.
The British government took a different decision,' he added. 'They were not
prepared to contribute in a broad realignment.'
